# gen132 (L16/L19): CHAINED abduction — the backward dual of gen130's forward
# sweep. When the premise that would entail a goal is ITSELF derivable, the rule
# engine runs backwards through the whole chain to the ROOT fact you could
# actually supply, and reports the inference spine. Multi-step inference to the
# missing premise, computed from the real rules.

# No rule at all: honestly nothing would make it so.
> what would make socrates a wizard?
< I have no rule that would make anything a wizard, so I can't say what would.

# A two-link chain: mortal <- man <- human. Nothing about socrates is known yet.
> every man is a mortal
< Learned rule: mortal(X) :- man(X).
> every human is a man
< Learned rule: man(X) :- human(X).
> is socrates a mortal?
< No.

# One step (man) wouldn't be acquirable — it's derived too — so abduction chains
# past it to the root premise (human) and shows the spine it would travel.
> what would make socrates a mortal?
< If you told me that socrates is a human, then socrates would be a mortal — by human -> man -> mortal.

# Supply the root: the consequence propagates the WHOLE chain (human -> man ->
# mortal) and gen103 volunteers it — abduction and self-correction, end to end.
> socrates is a human
< Learned: human(socrates). Now socrates is a mortal after all.
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.
